  "Idea": "This paper proposes H-CurriculumKG, a unified multi-task framework that jointly optimizes hyper-relational knowledge graph (KG) embedding and contrastive learning through a novel integration of hierarchical ontology-guided curriculum learning and second-order gradient alignment. The core innovation lies in recognizing that both tasks—link prediction over complex hyper-triplets and contrastive representation learning—can benefit from an adaptive training schedule that progresses from general, high-level concepts to specific, fine-grained facts. To achieve this, H-CurriculumKG introduces three synergistic components: (1) a Hierarchical Concept Scheduler (HCS) that leverages ontology trees (e.g., from schema.org or domain-specific taxonomies) to assign curriculum weights to facts based on their depth in the conceptual hierarchy, enabling early focus on broad relational patterns before transitioning to rare, nested hyper-relations; (2) a Second-Order Gradient Alignment Module (SGAM), which extends beyond first-order gradient cosine similarity by computing Hessian-weighted task relevance to stabilize optimization in high-curvature regions of the loss landscape, thereby preventing one objective from overshooting due to sharp gradients; and (3) a Concept-Aware Hard Negative Generator (CHNG) that synthesizes challenging yet semantically coherent negatives by perturbing entity roles within shared ontological contexts (e.g., replacing 'enzyme' with another 'catalyst' rather than a random protein), enhancing contrastive discrimination without introducing noise.\n\nThe model employs a shared relational path-enhanced Transformer encoder capable of encoding both primary triplets and associated qualifier pairs, with dual output heads: one using a modified pLogicNet scorer for hyper-triplet scoring, and another computing contrastive loss over augmented entity views generated via hierarchical subgraph masking and type-consistent attribute dropout. Crucially, the HCS dynamically modulates both batch composition and loss weighting during training—early epochs emphasize frequent, shallow-concept facts and stronger contrastive regularization, while later stages amplify rare, deep-concept hyper-relations with refined gradient balancing via SGAM. This curriculum is learned end-to-end using a lightweight controller network that observes embedding stability, task convergence rates, and concept coverage statistics.\n\nBy aligning optimization dynamics with semantic abstraction levels, H-CurriculumKG enables smoother convergence, better generalization to zero-shot relations, and improved transferability of embeddings. It addresses limitations in existing approaches: unlike GRAD-SAM-KG, it doesn’t just react to gradient conflicts but anticipates them through structured curricula; unlike HyperCL, it integrates hierarchy into training scheduling, not just representation modeling; and unlike SimKGC, its negatives are conceptually grounded rather than randomly sampled. The result is a more cognitively plausible, efficient, and robust multi-task learner for complex KGs.",
  "Title": "H-CurriculumKG: Hierarchical Curriculum Learning with Second-Order Gradient Alignment for Joint Hyper-Relational KG Embedding and Contrastive Learning",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of four phases. First, we implement H-CurriculumKG using StarE and pLogicNet as base encoders, integrated with a contrastive module using InfoNCE loss over ontology-aware augmentations. We evaluate on WikiPeople, JF17K, and FB-ADE, enriched with extracted ontology hierarchies via schema alignment and clustering of relation types. Second, we conduct ablation studies removing HCS, SGAM, and CHNG individually, measuring MRR, Hits@1/10, and clustering F1 across full-shot, few-shot, and zero-shot relation splits. Third, we analyze training dynamics using gradient curvature metrics (e.g., spectral norm of Hessian approximations), concept coverage tracking, and t-SNE visualizations of embedding evolution across curriculum stages. Fourth, we test transfer performance on downstream tasks like relation clustering and inductive QA using a reduced version of the EmbedKGQA setup. Ideal outcomes include: (1) ≥7% improvement in MRR over single-task and naive multi-task baselines; (2) faster convergence with 30% reduction in training oscillation; (3) superior few/zero-shot link prediction (+10% Hits@1); (4) higher-quality negatives validated via human evaluation; and (5) demonstrable correlation between curriculum progression and embedding coherence.",
