  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework, GRAD-SAM-KG (Gradient-Aware Dual Optimization with Fact-Aware Sampling for Knowledge Graphs), designed to enable stable and effective multi-task training by simultaneously optimizing hyper-relational knowledge graph (KG) embedding and contrastive learning objectives. The central challenge in such joint training lies in the misalignment of gradient magnitudes and directions between the two objectives: link prediction typically exerts stronger gradients due to dense supervision signals, causing contrastive learning—which relies on structural similarity—to be suppressed during backpropagation. To address this, GRAD-SAM-KG introduces two core innovations: (1) a Gradient-Aware Task Balancing Module (GTBM) that dynamically adjusts the contribution of each loss component by analyzing layer-wise gradient norms and cosine similarities between task gradients, thereby preventing dominance and promoting convergence harmony; and (2) a Fact-Aware Adaptive Sampler (FAS) that prioritizes hyper-relational facts based on their structural uniqueness, relational rarity, and contrastive difficulty, ensuring that both rare but semantically rich facts and hard negative samples are adequately represented during training.\n\nThe GTBM operates by computing per-layer gradient statistics during each mini-batch update, estimating the degree of conflict or synergy between the embedding and contrastive losses using gradient cosine similarity. When high conflict is detected, GTBM applies a learnable scaling factor derived from a lightweight gating network conditioned on gradient meta-features (e.g., variance, sparsity, norm ratio). This enables automatic down-weighting of the dominant objective without manual tuning. Meanwhile, FAS leverages a dynamic queue of historical embedding distances and relation frequency statistics to identify underrepresented fact types and high-uncertainty entity pairs. It then constructs mixed batches containing both standard and strategically sampled hard negatives for contrastive learning, enhancing representation discrimination.\n\nAdditionally, the framework integrates a shared encoder backbone—such as a relation-path enhanced Transformer or GNN—with dual output heads: one for scoring hyper-triplets via a modified TuckER or pLogicNet scorer, and another for computing contrastive loss over augmented views of entities generated through relation-subgraph masking and attribute dropout. The entire system is trained end-to-end with synchronized updates, enabling cross-objective feedback loops. By unifying optimization dynamics and data sampling under a single coherent strategy, GRAD-SAM-KG aims to achieve superior performance in link prediction, particularly for zero-shot and few-shot relations, while also producing more transferable and robust embeddings suitable for downstream tasks like clustering or retrieval. This approach advances beyond prior art by shifting focus from static loss combination to adaptive, runtime-aware optimization control—a critical step toward reliable multi-objective learning in complex semantic spaces.",
